args: ...No Mukuroshu in the area,\nand no traps from Doman.
Well, ain't that swell! Let's keep 'er movin'\nin that case!
You don't look happy, Lord Seimei.
No traps? No enemies? NONE?\nThis is going far too easily.
But don't that mean Doman just didn't\nexpect us to track down his hideout\nand come a'runnin' after him?
(Could that be possible? Could he truly\nnot have predicted this?)
(This is DOMAN we're talking about,\nafter all—and the Doman I know is\ncunning and sly beyond measure.)
(There was no better ally...\nbut also no greater enemy.)
Ah, Seimei. You do indeed hold promise.\nJust look how easily you wiped out all of\nthe enemy shikigami!
It is an utter delight that a practitioner\nas skilled as you should look to join\nthe Bureau of Onmyodo!

Hmph. You'll forgive me if I don't puff my
chest in pride at slaying a few pathetic
shikigami brought into creation by
unsanctioned onmyoji.

This fight only confirms the skill of our
enemy—and it seems they are nothing
special at the end of the day. If we mount
a quick frontal assault, they are done for.
Hmm. Perhaps. But just to be safe,\nlet us proceed with caution.
Hmm? Why are you picking up talismans\nfrom the shikigami we defeated?
Now just stand there, as you were.
You revived the enemy shikigami and\nmade them obey you? Why?
If the enemy realizes their shikigami have\nbeen slain, it will raise the alarm.
On the other hand, if we feed them false\ninformation suggesting that naught is\namiss, we invite their negligence.
That seems like a lot of trouble to go to\nfor such a weak pack of foes.
As I said, we're simply being cautious.
When onmyoji clash, the battle begins\nlong before they meet face-to-face.

Think, for example, of the destruction of
evidence and creation of false stand-ins.
Yes, the battle is begun long before the
parties come before one another.
Unbelievable! What those villagers\nsaid to us...
You sent that shikigami off at great speed,\nyet I understood the area to be free of\ntraps or enemies.
I sent it to do recon on the dragon-vein\nspring Doman was headed for.
I can't believe that I, of all people, was so\ncareless as to leap on the first little scrap\nof information dangled in front of me!
What the villager told us was actually\nrather strange when you think about it.
A man as distinctly sharp as Doman\nwould never just casually drop his\ndestination in front of others.
...I knew it. The dragon-vein spring\nis completely abandoned.
Boy, this is all over my poor little head,\nI tell ya what. I'm more confused than\na cow caught in a twister!
Are ya sayin' the villagers told us fibs?
No, you stupid fox—DOMAN told ＂fibs.＂\nThe villagers deceived us unwittingly.
He intentionally said something false\nonce he knew they would overhear.
In so doing, he could throw off the\nintruders who had infiltrated that hideout.
Then he already knew we were after him?
But how?! We was super careful!
It was likely when we defeated those\nMukuroshu grunts in the forest.

Fell onmyodo knows no ethical bounds.
He could've embedded talismans within
their bodies, or other such methods, to
inform him of their deaths.
Disgust won't solve anything, though.\nWe need an actual plan.
Which means we're\nback at square one. Tch.
Why, whatever is amiss, my children?\nI see three long faces that look to quiver\nbeneath the clouded skies above.
It is indeed I, Marvelous Naoto—and my\nheart leaps with abject delight that we\nmight meet again after so long a spell!

...Or perhaps it is better to say that I am
Rikugo, high-level shikigami of the Bureau
of Onmyodo, and I have hastened to your
side that I might deliver my report.
